# DeSDI Development Workspace Context

## 1. Project Context & Vision
DeSDI (Decentralized Spatial Data Infrastructure) bridges the gap
between scientific computing and decentralized networks. The system is
built as an open-source, high-performance monorepo designed to parse
multi-dimensional scientific files (.h5, .laz, COGs), shard them into
network-optimized blocks, map them to IPFS CIDs, and register them via
an Immutable Spatial Registry on the Filecoin Virtual Machine (FVM).

## 2. Core Codebase Rules
- **Monorepo Architecture:** All applications, smart contracts,
  planning documents, and infrastructure configurations must reside
  within this single repository.
- **No Manual Infrastructure:** Every infrastructure resource, sandbox
  environment, and automated runner track must be explicitly defined
  using AWS CDK in the `/infra` folder.
- **Planning Gate:** Before code execution begins for any major
  feature, a comprehensive Markdown-formatted Product Requirement
  Document (PRD) must be compiled in the `docs/planning/` directory.

## 3. Technology Stack & Coding Standards
- **Ingestion & Parsing Engine:** High-performance, low-level
  open-source libraries written in modern C++23.
- **Smart Contract Layer:** Solidity/Yul or Rust targeted for the
  Filecoin Virtual Machine (FVM) environment.
- **Infrastructure as Code (IaC):** AWS CDK utilizing Python.
- **Database Layer:** Serverless PostgreSQL (Neon) for isolated,
  dynamic database staging branches.

## 4. Automation & Continuous Integration Rules (GitLab)
- **GitLab Issues Integration:** Implementation tasks are categorized
  into independent, granular chunks (tasks designed to be
  completed within 30 minutes of straight coding).
- **Label Trust Boundary:** Automation scripts only interact with
  GitLab issues explicitly containing both the `lane:cdx-any` and
  `ready` labels.
- **Sandboxed Runner Isolation:** Self-hosted GitLab CI/CD runners
  executing processing tasks must be ephemeral, single-job execution
  environments isolated cleanly in AWS with tightly scoped IAM
  privileges.
